{"abstract": "For now, SoftBank, through its stake in Alibaba, is one of the few ways for public investors to gain exposure to the Chinese e-commerce giant. But that advantage will disappear when Alibaba goes public, writes Una Galani of Reuters Breakingviews.", "web_url": "https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/27/softbanks-investment-in-alibaba-may-turn-into-a-burden/", "snippet": "For now, SoftBank, through its stake in Alibaba, is one of the few ways for public investors to gain exposure to the Chinese e-commerce giant. But that advantage will disappear when Alibaba goes public, writes Una Galani of Reuters Breakingviews.", "lead_paragraph": "SoftBank\u2019s investment in Alibaba must be one of the most successful of all time. Masayoshi Son, the billionaire chief executive of SoftBank, injected $20 million into the Chinese e-commerce giant in 2000. Today, that 36.7 percent stake accounts for a large chunk of Japanese group\u2019s market value. As Alibaba heads toward an initial public offering, however, Mr. Son\u2019s investment blessing may become a burden.", "source": "The New York Times", "multimedia": [{"rank": 0, "subtype": "xlarge", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/28/business/dbpix-softbank/dbpix-softbank-articleLarge.jpg", "height": 415, "width": 600, "subType": "xlarge", "crop_name": "articleLarge", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2014/02/28/business/dbpix-softbank/dbpix-softbank-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": 600, "xlargeheight": 415}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "jumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/28/business/dbpix-softbank/dbpix-softbank-jumbo.jpg", "height": 708, "width": 1024, "subType": "jumbo", "crop_name": "jumbo", "legacy": {}}, {"rank": 0, "subtype": "superJumbo", "caption": null, "credit": null, "type": "image", "url": "images/2014/02/28/business/dbpix-softbank/dbpix-softbank-superJumbo.jpg", "height": 1416, "width": 2048, "subType": "superJumbo", "crop_name": "su